GitLab to Bitbucket Migration — Detailed Explanation
Why This Migration Happened
JnJ decided to move from GitLab (self-hosted) to Bitbucket Server (at sourcecode.jnj.com/projects/ASX-JJJC) as the company's standard version control platform. Scope had deep integration with GitLab — it automatically created repos, managed user access, set up branch rules, and pushed files. All of that had to be rewritten for Bitbucket's completely different API.

What the "Scope Code" Feature Does
When a scientist or researcher creates a project in Scope (like a drug study), Scope automatically:

Creates a code repository for that project (a place to store research code, R scripts, data templates)
Sets up folder structure (Code/, Data/, Documents/, Output/)
Adds a .gitignore file and project-specific templates
Assigns permissions — who can push code, who can only read
Protects the main branch so nobody can accidentally break things
Previously this all went to GitLab. Now it all goes to Bitbucket.

Phase-by-Phase Breakdown
Phase 1: Core Repository Creation (Dec 2025 – Jan 2026)
What was built:

createRepo(repoName) — Creates a new repository in Bitbucket under the ASX-JJJC project using the SA-PRD-SDSFORGE service account
Repo names are auto-generated as URL-safe slugs (lowercase, hyphens, max 100 chars)
Uses Basic Auth with the service account credentials (rotatable without restart)
Technical challenge solved: Bitbucket auto-initializes new repos with a commit on main. When Scope tried to push its initial files, git sent an oldSHA=0000...0000 "create" packet — but the branch already existed. This caused "cannot lock ref: reference already exists" errors. The fix: clone the repo first (with retry logic — up to 5 attempts, 1 second apart, because Bitbucket's init is async), then commit on top of it as a fast-forward push. No --force needed.

Phase 2: Branch Permissions & Access Control (Jan – Mar 2026)
What was built: The applyBranchRules(repoSlug, users) function applies 4 branch restriction rules to main:

read-only — Nobody can push directly
no-deletes — Branch can't be deleted
fast-forward-only — No force pushes
pull-request-only — Changes require a PR
Who gets exempt (can bypass the rules):

Project leads — get full write access + exemption from all restrictions
Project collaborators — get REPO_WRITE permission + exemptions
For SMMC projects, the submitter is also added
Graceful failure handling: If a user hasn't logged into Bitbucket yet (LDAP users only appear after first login), granting permission fails. Instead of crashing and deleting the repo, the code returns HTTP 207 (Partial Success) with a message like: "Repository created successfully; however, permissions could not be set for: username. Please ensure they are members of ITS-ASx-SCM-JJJC-SCMContributors."

Phase 3: Dynamic Member Management — Adding/Removing Users (Mar – Apr 2026)
The problem: Bitbucket has no partial-update API for branch restrictions. You can't just "add a user to an existing rule." You must delete the rule and recreate it with the updated user list.

What addProjectMember(repoSlug, username) does:

Grants REPO_WRITE permission at the repo level
Fetches ALL existing branch restrictions
For each restriction where the user ISN'T already exempt:
Deletes the restriction
Recreates it with the same rules + the new user added to exemptions
What removeProjectMember(repoSlug, username) does:

Removes repo-level permission (treats 404 as success — already gone)
Fetches all branch restrictions
For each restriction where the user IS exempt:
Deletes it
Recreates without that user (preserving all other users)
Phase 4: Project Updates & Collaborator Sync (Apr – May 2026)
What updateProject(payload, currentSlug, oLead, nLead, collaborators, leads) does: When someone edits a project in Scope (renames it, changes the lead, adds collaborators):

Renames the Bitbucket repo (slug changes)
Adds new lead to branch restriction exemptions
Removes old lead (only if they differ, case-insensitive comparison)
Collaborators are synced — new ones added, removed ones revoked
Phase 5: File Operations Without Credentials in URLs (Jan 2026)
Security concern: The old GitLab code embedded credentials in git clone URLs. This is visible in process lists and logs.

Solution: Credentials are written to a temporary file (mode 0o600 = owner-read-only), referenced via git -c "credential.helper=store --file=/tmp/.git-cred-xxxxx", and always deleted in a finally block — even if the operation crashes.

updateContent(repoSlug, actions) — for updating existing repos:

Clones the repo (shallow, depth 1) into a temp directory
Applies file actions (create/update/delete)
Commits and pushes
Cleans up temp dir + credential file in finally
fetchFile(repoSlug, filePath) — for reading files:

Bitbucket returns file content as lines[] (paginated), not base64 like GitLab
The code reassembles all pages, joins lines, and encodes to base64
Returns the exact same shape as the old GitLab response ({ body: { content: base64 } }) so no other code had to change
Phase 6: Group Management (Mar – Apr 2026)
Replaces GitLab group operations:

createBitbucketGroup / deleteBitbucketGroup — Admin-level group CRUD
addUserToBitbucketGroup / removeUserFromBitbucketGroup — Manage group membership








